T1  - Crisis dynamics of implied default recovery ratios: Evidence from Russia and Argentina
AU  - Merrick Jr, John J
JO  - Journal of Banking & Finance
VL  - 25
IS  - 10
SP  - 1921
EP  - 1939
PY  - 2001
DA  - 2001/10/01/
SN  - 0378-4266
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/S0378-4266(00)00165-5
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0378426600001655
KW  - Credit crisis
KW  - Default risk
KW  - Recovery value
KW  - Investments
AB  - This paper extracts both the implied default recovery ratio and the risk-neutral default probability term structure for Russian Federation and Republic of Argentina US dollar Eurobonds during the 1998 Russian default crisis. This crisis provides a unique window into the impact of changing default probabilities and recovery ratio assumptions on credit-sensitive sovereign bond prices. For the Russian Eurobonds, the sample paths suggest a two-phase crisis revaluation. Shifts in default probabilities account for most of the initial price collapse. Marked decreases in the implied default recovery ratio dominate the second phase. Investors never cut their recovery value assumptions for Argentine debt.
ER  - 

